docs.lead_paragraph: OLYMPIA FIELDS, Ill. — Golf played on even as other sports in America stopped, and it gave Cameron Champ a chance to speak out at the BMW Championship.

headline.main: Champ Makes Statement on Racial Justice as BMW Championship Begins

docs.abstract: The Trump team’s approach to the task of pigeonholing the challenger looked less focused than those used in 2004 and 2012.
docs.snippet: The Trump team’s approach to the task of pigeonholing the challenger looked less focused than those used in 2004 and 2012.
docs.lead_paragraph: The last two presidential re-election campaigns followed a similar playbook: define the opposition early on the most important issue, emphasize a few cultural wedge issues to rally the base while appealing to a few swing voters, and reinvigorate supporters at the convention. It was enough for George W. Bush in 2004 and Barack Obama in 2012 to flip their approval ratings from negative to positive, and to win re-election.

headline.main: Conventions Can Boost the Incumbent. Did It Work This Time?
headline.print_headline: Bush and Obama Saw  Post-Convention Bumps.  Can Trump Expect One?

docs.abstract: The government could revive an idea to make it mandatory for large companies to report their pay gaps by ethnicity.
docs.snippet: The government could revive an idea to make it mandatory for large companies to report their pay gaps by ethnicity.
docs.lead_paragraph: Nearly two years ago, the British government seemed to be on the verge of doing something truly novel about racial and ethnic inequality. Theresa May, the prime minister at the time, had adopted a plan to root out one of the causes of differences in incomes that would “create a fairer and more diverse work force,” she said.

headline.main: In Britain, an Idea to Reduce Racial Inequality Gains Momentum
headline.print_headline: A U.K. Move To Air Out Salary Gaps

docs.abstract: When my daughters look back on the plague year and all its horrors, I hope they also remember the flowers.
docs.snippet: When my daughters look back on the plague year and all its horrors, I hope they also remember the flowers.
docs.lead_paragraph: Way back in March, definitely after 15 Days to Stop the Spread; maybe during 30 Days to Stop the Spread, when we were all heading toward the realization that we had no real plan to stop the spread, I ordered a window-garden flower starter kit.

docs.abstract: The sheriff, Bobby F. Kimbrough Jr., said he cried after watching video of the events that led to John Neville’s death last year in a North Carolina jail. Portions of the footage were released on Wednesday.

docs.lead_paragraph: A North Carolina sheriff apologized on Tuesday to the family of a Black man who died last year after being restrained at a jail, a day before officials released videos showing the episode that led to the man’s death.

headline.main: Sheriff Apologizes to Family of Inmate Who Died After Being Restrained

docs.abstract: The pandemic has inspired a flurry of new and novel items — and given ordinary ones new meanings.
docs.snippet: The pandemic has inspired a flurry of new and novel items — and given ordinary ones new meanings.
docs.lead_paragraph: Plastic bubbles that hover over restaurant tables. Rods for contactless elevator-button-pushing. Portable seats that attach to lampposts, for shoppers waiting outside crowd-controlled stores. Dresses with skirts that have a six-foot radius. Podlike enclosures to keep gym-goers separate. A plastic sleeve that enables hugging at nursing homes. Masks in every imaginable form.

headline.main: The Strange Lives of Objects in the Coronavirus Era
